    pearls: ["Never rely solely on the computer-generated ECG interpretation — it has a 15-20% error rate for significant findings including STEMI, heart blocks, and arrhythmias. Always over-read every ECG yourself", "STEMI equivalents are just as dangerous as classic STEMI but are frequently missed: de Winter T-waves (proximal LAD occlusion), new LBBB with ischemic symptoms, and posterior MI (isolated ST depression V1-V3). Learn these patterns", "Hyperkalemia produces a predictable ECG progression: peaked T-waves (K+ 5.5-6.5) → flattened P-waves/PR prolongation (6.5-7.5) → widened QRS (7.5-8.0) → sine wave (>8.0) → cardiac arrest. This progression can occur rapidly — the ECG is your early warning system"],
